Before we develop our app, we need to raise venture capital. In order to secure this funding, we need an experienced team of experts to help us finish validating our product vision, completing our product strategy and road-maps, figuring out product requirements, finding the perfect product market fit, and prototype testing.

The document and presentation requirements:

1. Business Model Innovation
Looking to build or innovate a new business model, putting together our Product Roadmap for our first MVP (Minimum Viable Product) and future development.

2. Monetization Formulation
Monetization is often the most difficult part of Product Strategy. Looking for in-depth knowledge in the industry to consult us on what gives you the best chance of revenue.

3. Branding and Positioning Matrix
Looking for help to fully understand where we fit in the marketplace and get the positioning and branding of our product right.

4. Habitual Dependence
Looking for some ways we can build psychological dependence within our product so we can have people coming back again and again.

9. Cost of MVP (Minimum Viable Product)
Unlike traditional development models, we want 100% control of our budget in order to hit our 'Budget Target'… based on our first MVP (the leanest, meanest, 'least investment possible' version of the product that is needed in order to launch to market and deliver the highest business value/ROI)

To wrap things up, this stage is essential to securing venture capital for our firm. We are looking for a team that will go above and beyond to blow us away. If the deliverables are up to our high standards, we will likely use those funds to hire your firm to develop our MVP.

comment: I have made a drill and practise workbook in Microsoft Excel. Children choose the times table by selecting the factor range and press start. A count down timer is initiated and the first set of factors appears. The child types in their response and the response is ticked (correct) or crossed (wrong) and the next set of factors is displayed beneath the first. The child can now choose to correct any previous error or proceed to respond to the next set of factors. This process continues for up to 20 factor sets. On entering the last answer, the count down timer is stopped and the duration (speed) displayed along with the number of correct out of the number of presented factors (b/w - accuracy). If the child was wrong on this last set, they make the correction and the speed and accuracy calculations are updated on "ENTER". This information is also copied and pasted to a worksheet within the workbook to record the child's history of speed and accuracy on each occasion they complete a set of factors.
